endirilmektedir.\r\nÄ°nsan figÃ¼rlerinin uzunluÄŸu,9-14 cm. arasÄ±nda deÄŸiÅŸiyor. DaÄŸ keÄŸilerinin boyu 18-25 cm. geniÅŸliÄŸi ise 30-36 cm. arasÄ±ndadÄ±r.\r\n',NULL,0,'2026-02-22 09:52:36','Sinek Stream and its Spring and the Rock Shelter','It is a water source originating north of Ã§ermik and providing life to the villages in the region. With its surrounding caves and interesting rock formations, it is a focal point for athletes and nature lovers.\r\nLocated 7.5 km north of Ã§ermik, near the source of the Sinek Stream, this shelter, where human and animal paintings depicting a hunting expedition were discovered, has been identified as the oldest known paintings in Anatolia.\r\n\r\nThe paintings, unearthed in June 2005 by Prof. Dr. Oktay Belli, Director of the Eurasian Archaeology Institute at Istanbul University, are located in an area of Ã”Ã‡Ã¯Ã”Ã‡Ã¯1.60 x 2.40 meters. It is estimated that the 11 archers organizing the hunting expedition depicted in the paintings lived between 15,000 and 13,000 years ago (Upper Paleolithic and Mesolithic periods). Prof. Dr. Belli states that a section of the rock shelter, where 16 animal figures and 11 human figures were found, is covered with a limestone layer, and that other paintings are located beneath this layer. Archaeozoologist Assoc. Prof. Dr. Vedat ONAR believes that fourteen of the animals are mountain goats, one is a kid (young goat), and the other may be a feline. The main subject of the rock paintings is various game animals and human figures hunting them with bows and arrows. Prof. Dr. BELLÄ° points out that a similar hunting scene depicting people hunting mountain goats with bows and arrows has not been found in Anatolia to date, and says, \"The 11 hunters depicted here are currently the oldest known hunters in Anatolia.\"',''),(19,3,'Haburman KÃ¶prÃ¼sÃ¼','Historical','1179 yÄ±lÄ±nda Artuklular dÃ¶neminde ZÃ¼beyde Hatun tarafÄ±ndan yaptÄ±rÄ±lan kÃ¶prÃ¼, Sinek Ã§ayÄ± Ã¼zerindedir. â”œÂ£ÄŸ gÃ¶zlÃ¼ yapÄ±sÄ± ve kalker