Bey Mosque after its founder.\r\n\r\nDevelopment: The mosque was not built all at once; it was enlarged over time with additions. It was damaged during the Mongol invasion, underwent a major repair during the reign of the Anatolian Seljuk Sultan Alaeddin Keykubad II, and its minaret was added during this period.\r\n\r\n2. Architectural Features\r\nThe mosque consists of two main sections that bear traces of two different architectural periods:\r\n\r\nCrown Gate: The crown gate, belonging to the Shah Ali Bey section on the east, reflects the characteristic features of Seljuk and Artuklu stonework. The geometric decorations and spiral columns above the gate are noteworthy.\r\n\r\nDome and Roof: The harem (main prayer area) of the building has a square plan. Its roof is in the form of a conical roof covered with tiles, resting on an octagonal drum.\r\n\r\nMaterials: Crushed stone is used in the exterior walls, while more carefully cut stone and basalt are used around the doors and windows.\r\n\r\nCapacity: With a usable area of Ã”Ã‡Ã¯Ã”Ã‡Ã¯approximately 700 square meters, the mosque can accommodate nearly a thousand worshippers at the same time.\r\n\r\n3. Prominent Details\r\nSpiritual Value: As the oldest mosque in the district, it bears the title of \"Grand Mosque\" and is the spiritual center of Ã§ermik.\r\n\r\nInscriptions and Emblems: Some emblems on the entrance gate, which have not been fully deciphered, are thought to represent the date of the mosque\'s construction or the seal of the family that commissioned it.\r\n\r\nLocation: Due to its location in Tepe Mahallesi, it is associated with the \"HanbaÅŸÄ±\" area in daily life by the bazaar merchants and local people.',''),(35,3,'FÄ±rat Nehri','Nature','FÄ±rat Nehri, dÃ¼nyanÄ±n en uzun ve tarihin akÄ±ÅŸÄ±nÄ± ÅŸekillendirmiÅŸ bÃ¼yÃ¼k nehirlerinden biridir. Ã§ermik ÄŸevresinden geÄŸen nehir; turkuaz yeÅŸili sularÄ±, vadileri ve ÄŸevresindeki doÄŸal gÃ¼zellikleriyle fotoÄŸraf tutkunlarÄ±nÄ±n ve doÄŸa gezginlerinin 